{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem asks for the minimum number of set bits in the product of 2023 and n. This is equivalent to finding the minimum Hamming weight of a multiple of 2023. Since 2023 is not a power of 2, we need to investigate the properties of multiples of 2023 in binary.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "factorization_and_properties",
      "instructions": "Factorize the number 2023 into its prime components and determine if it shares any common factors with 2. Identify if 2023 is coprime to 2."
    },
    {
      "label": "binary_weight_search",
      "instructions": "Find the smallest integer k such that there exists an integer n where the number of ones in the binary representation of 2023*n is k. Test k=1 (is 2023*n a power of 2?), then k=2 (is 2023*n equal to 2^a + 2^b?), and so on. For k=2, check if 2023 divides 2^a + 2^b for some a, b. This is equivalent to checking if 2^a + 2^b is congruent to 0 modulo 2023, or 2^a is congruent to -2^b modulo 2023."
    },
    {
      "label": "modular_exponentiation_check",
      "instructions": "Check if there exist integers a and b such that 2^a + 2^b is a multiple of 2023. This is equivalent to checking if 2^(a-b) is congruent to -1 modulo 2023 (assuming a > b). Calculate the order of 2 modulo 2023 or check if -1 is in the cyclic subgroup generated by 2 modulo 2023."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the prime factorization to confirm 2023 is odd. Use the modular exponentiation results to determine if k=1 is possible (it is not, as 2023 is not a power of 2). Use the results from the k=2 check (the existence of a solution to 2^x = -1 mod 2023) to determine if k=2 is the minimum. If k=2 is impossible, proceed to check k=3."
}

